=== HYPOTHESIS L: Tournament has Z_2 x Z_2 symmetry structure ===
  n=5, m=6
  Backbone edges: [(1, 0), (2, 1), (3, 2), (4, 3)]
  Non-backbone tiles: [(2, 0), (3, 0), (3, 1), (4, 0), (4, 1), (4, 2)]

  bits=7:
    T ≅ T^op: False
    T ≅ T_flip: False
    T_flip ≅ T^op: False
    T^op ≅ T_flip^op: False


=== Orbits under <complement, GS-flip> ===
  n=5: 32 orbits under GS flip only
  Orbit sizes: [2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2, 2]
  Fixed points: 0, Pairs: 32
  (Expect: 0 fixed points, 32 pairs)


=== HYPOTHESIS M: Tournament as quantum state ===
  The transfer matrix M being symmetric is analogous to
  time-reversal symmetry in a quantum walk on the tournament graph.
  This is the most speculative hypothesis but could connect to
  existing quantum walk literature.


=== HYPOTHESIS N: 1+2^{n-2} from binary recursion ===
  bits=all tournament:
  n=3: H=3, 1+2^(n-2)=3, diff=0, t3=1, scores=[1, 1, 1]
  n=4: H=5, 1+2^(n-2)=5, diff=0, t3=2, scores=[1, 1, 2, 2]
  n=5: H=9, 1+2^(n-2)=9, diff=0, t3=3, scores=[1, 1, 2, 3, 3]
  n=6: H=17, 1+2^(n-2)=17, diff=0, t3=4, scores=[1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 4]
  n=7: H=31, 1+2^(n-2)=33, diff=-2, t3=5, scores=[1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 5]
  n=8: H=57, 1+2^(n-2)=65, diff=-8, t3=6, scores=[1, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 6]
